The S-A-A blueprint, where each module fits.

The A-W-S Certified Solutions Architect Associate exam, S-A-A-C-zero-three, tests architectural competence across the platform, and its blueprint maps cleanly onto the thirteen modules before this one. There are four domains.

Design Secure Architectures is thirty percent, and it draws on module two for I-A-M and Organizations, module eleven for K-M-S, W-A-F, Shield, and GuardDuty, and module six for V-P-C, security groups, and N-A-C-Ls. Design Resilient Architectures is twenty-six percent, from module three for E-L-B and Auto Scaling, module eight for R-D-S Multi-A-Z and Aurora, and module thirteen for D-R and Backup. Design High-Performing Architectures is twenty-four percent, spanning module three compute, module four serverless, module five storage, module seven CloudFront, and modules eight through ten for data and integration. And Design Cost-Optimized Architectures is twenty percent, from module thirteen for Reserved Instances, Savings Plans, Spot, and S3 tiers, module five for S3 classes, and module three for instance choice.

Modules one, foundations, and twelve, observability and governance, cut across all four domains, and module fourteen, this one, is the integration. There is no S-A-A topic that isn't covered somewhere in the previous modules; the course is the blueprint. Two things to note. First, Security at thirty percent is the single largest domain, so invest your study time proportionally. Second, the weights are about breadth of questions, not difficulty; a resilient-architecture question can be every bit as demanding as a security one. Study to the domain weights, but answer every question with the same discipline: name the requirement, eliminate the impossible, and choose on the stated preference.
